cs.DC, cs.DS, cs.PL, cs.DM, cs.AL 

Reasoning: 
1. cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) - This paper is primarily focused on developing optimal parallel algorithms in a specific parallel computing model, the binary-forking model. Therefore, it is highly likely that this paper belongs to the cs.DC sub-category. 
2. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) - The paper discusses optimal algorithms for a variety of fundamental problems such as sorting, semisorting, list ranking, tree contraction, range minima, and set union, intersection, and difference. These are all topics that fall under the cs.DS sub-category. 
3. cs.PL (Programming Languages) - The paper mentions that variants of the binary-forking model are widely used in practice in languages such as Cilk and Java Fork-Join. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the cs.PL sub-category. 
4. cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) - The paper discusses range minima, which is a topic that falls under the cs.DM sub-category. 
5. cs.AL (Computational Complexity) - The paper discusses the costs of the algorithms in terms of work and span, which are measures of computational complexity. Therefore, it is possible that this paper also belongs to the cs.AL sub-category.
